col_q: An ellipse passes through the foci of the hyperbola, \(9x^2-4y^2=36\) and its major and minor axes lie along the transverse and conjugate axes of the hyperbola respectively. If the product of eccentricities of the two conics is \(\frac{1}{2}\), then which of the following points does not lie on the ellipse? \(\left(\sqrt{13},\:0\right)\) \(\left(\frac{\sqrt{39}}{2},\:\sqrt{3}\right)\) \(\left(\frac{1}{2}\sqrt{13},\:\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)\) \(\left(\sqrt{\frac{13}{2}},\:\sqrt{6}\right)\)

row_q: If the points \((1,1,\lambda)\) and \((-3,0,1)\) are equidistant from the plane, \(3x+4y-12z+13=0\), then \(\lambda\) satisfies the equation \(3x^2-10x+7=0\) \(3x^2+10x+7=0\) \(3x^2+10x-13=0\) \(3x^2-10x+21=0\)
col_q: If the points \((1,\:1,\:\lambda)\) and \(\left(-3,\:0,\:1\right)\) are equidistant from the plane, \(3x+4y-12z+13=0\), then \(\lambda\) satisfies the equation: \(3x^2-10x+7=0\) \(3x^2+10x+7=0\) \(3x^2+10x-13=0\) \(3x^2-10x+21=0\)

row_q: If the shortest distance between the lines \(\frac{x-1}{\alpha}=\frac{y+1}{-1}=\frac{z}{1},\left(\alpha\ne-1\right)\) and \(x+y+z+1=0=2x-y+z+3\) is \(\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\), then the value of \(\alpha\) is \(-\frac{16}{19}\) \(-\frac{19}{16}\) \(\frac{32}{19}\) \(\frac{19}{32}\)
